{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Famously, Meta's Galactica LLM [8] was trained using a massive corpus of scientific literature and was able to provide realisticsounding, albeit totally hallucinated, scientific articles.Essentially, a fine-tuned LLM can act in a desired way, but it still suffers from a lack of ground truth to avoid hallucinations.Finally, fine-tuning is expensive.",
    "In this paper we host a large portion of the chatbot locally, but the LLM itself is still a GPT3.5 model hosted by OpenAI.",
    "Finetuning GPT3.5 can cost hundreds to thousands of dollars depending on the size of the fine-tuning dataset [9].",
    "If we were to use a locally hosted model as well, our own experiments show that without significant computational resources fine-tuning is practically impossible.",
    "Indeed, our own set of High-Performance Computers, costing a total of nearly $22,000 as of the time of this writing, are capable of fine tuning only the smallest and least capable language models."
  ],
